## 8. System Flow Diagram

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User opens / ] --> B[Selects symptoms\nduration + risk factors]
    B --> C{POST /predict}
    C --> D[Emergency check\nvs emergency_combos.json]
    D -- match --> E[🚨 Emergency Alert]
    D -- no match --> F[Build weighted\nfeature vector]
    F --> G[Ensemble: RF + SVM + NB\nsoft-voting]
    G --> H[Apply risk factor boosts]
    H --> I[Compute severity score\n→ dynamic threshold]
    I --> J{confidence ≥ threshold?}
    J -- yes --> K[Consult Not Required]
    J -- no --> L[⚠ Consult Doctor Flag]
    K & L --> M[Differential explanation\n+ co-occurrence suggestions]
    E & M --> N[JSON response to browser]
    N --> O[result.html rendered]
    O --> P{User action?}
    P -- Follow-up --> Q[POST /followup\nmerge confirmed symptoms]
    P -- Re-diagnose --> R[POST /rediagnose\nadd more symptoms]
    P -- Download --> S[POST /download_pdf\nReportLab PDF streamed]
    Q & R --> G
```

---

## 9. How to Run

### Prerequisites
```
Python 3.10+
```

### Install dependencies
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### (First time only) Train the models
```bash
python train_model.py
```
This populates `models/` and `graphs/`. Takes 1–5 minutes depending on hardware.

### Start the web server
```bash
python app.py
```
The app runs at **http://localhost:5000** by default.

---

## 10. Key Design Decisions & Notes

- **Severity-weighted features** instead of raw binary inputs ensure clinically serious symptoms dominate the feature vector.
- **Soft-voting ensemble** (RF + SVM + NB) is used instead of any single model for more robust probability estimates. KNN is excluded from the ensemble because its `predict_proba` is degenerate (returns near-100% for one class).
- **Dynamic thresholds** mean the system is stricter about calling a high-severity case confident — protecting against false reassurance.
- **Post-hoc risk boosts** are a pragmatic way to personalize predictions without retraining per patient, applied only to the top-5 rescoring.
- The training dataset (Kaggle disease-prediction dataset) has only ~304 unique symptom patterns across 41 diseases, so RF and KNN achieve near-perfect scores not due to overfitting but due to dataset structure. The documentation and code comments explicitly acknowledge this limitation.
